# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: transcriptomics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Biologically relevant alternative splicing occurs as a normal phenomenon in eukaryotes, where it increases the number of proteins that can be encoded by the genome.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Alternative splicing was first observed in 1977.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The adenovirus produces five primary transcripts early in its infectious cycle, prior to viral DNA replication, and an additional one later, after DNA replication begins.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The early primary transcripts continue to be produced after DNA replication begins.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The additional primary transcript produced late in infection is large and comes from 5/6 of the 32kb adenovirus genome.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] This is much larger than any of the individual adenovirus mRNAs present in infected cells.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Researchers found that the primary RNA transcript produced by adenovirus type 2 in the late phase was spliced in many different ways, resulting in mRNAs encoding different viral proteins.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In addition, the primary transcript contained multiple polyadenylation sites, giving different 3' ends for the processed mRNAs.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In 1981, the first example of alternative splicing in a transcript from a normal, endogenous gene was characterized.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The gene encoding the thyroid hormone calcitonin was found to be alternatively spliced in mammalian cells.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The primary transcript from this gene contains 6 exons; the calcitonin mRNA contains exons 1–4, and terminates after a polyadenylation site in exon 4.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Another mRNA is produced from this pre-mRNA by skipping exon 4, and includes exons 1–3, 5, and 6.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] It encodes a protein known as CGRP (calcitonin gene related peptide).
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Examples of alternative splicing in immunoglobulin gene transcripts in mammals were also observed in the early 1980s.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Since then, many other examples of biologically relevant alternative splicing have been found in eukaryotes.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The "record-holder" for alternative splicing is a *D. melanogaster* gene called Dscam, which could potentially have 38,016 splice variants.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In 2021, it was discovered that the genome of adenovirus type 2, the adenovirus in which alternative splicing was first identified, was able to produce a much greater variety of splice variants than previously thought.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] By using next generation sequencing technology, researchers were able to update the human adenovirus type 2 transcriptome and document the presence of 904 splice variants produced by the virus through a complex pattern of alternative splicing.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Very few of these splice variants have been shown to be functional, a point that the authors raise in their paper.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Five basic modes of alternative splicing are generally recognized.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In addition to these primary modes of alternative splicing, there are two other main mechanisms by which different mRNAs may be generated from the same gene; multiple promoters and multiple polyadenylation sites.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Use of multiple promoters is properly described as a transcriptional regulation mechanism rather than alternative splicing; by starting transcription at different points, transcripts with different 5'-most exons can be generated.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] At the other end, multiple polyadenylation sites provide different 3' end points for the transcript.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Both of these mechanisms are found in combination with alternative splicing and provide additional variety in mRNAs derived from a gene.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] These modes describe basic splicing mechanisms, but may be inadequate to describe complex splicing events.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] For instance, the figure to the right shows three spliceforms from the mouse hyaluronidase 3 gene.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Comparing the exonic structure shown in the first line (green) with the one in the second line (yellow) shows intron retention, whereas the comparison between the second and the third spliceform (yellow vs. blue) exhibits exon skipping.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] A model nomenclature to uniquely designate all possible splicing patterns has recently been proposed.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] When the pre-mRNA has been transcribed from the DNA, it includes several introns and exons.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] (In nematodes, the mean is 4–5 exons and introns; in the fruit fly *Drosophila* there can be more than 100 introns and exons in one transcribed pre-mRNA.) The exons to be retained in the mRNA are determined during the splicing process.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The regulation and selection of splice sites are done by trans-acting splicing activator and splicing repressor proteins as well as cis-acting elements within the pre-mRNA itself such as exonic splicing enhancers and exonic splicing silencers.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The typical eukaryotic nuclear intron has consensus sequences defining important regions.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Each intron has the sequence GU at its 5' end.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The nucleotide at the branchpoint is always an A; the consensus around this sequence varies somewhat.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In humans the branch site consensus sequence is yUnAy.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The branch site is followed by a series of pyrimidines – the polypyrimidine tract – then by AG at the 3' end.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Splicing of mRNA is performed by an RNA and protein complex known as the spliceosome, containing snRNPs designated U1, U2, U4, U5, and U6 (U3 is not involved in mRNA splicing).
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] U1 binds to the 5' GU and U2, with the assistance of the U2AF protein factors, binds to the branchpoint A within the branch site.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The complex at this stage is known as the spliceosome A complex.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Formation of the A complex is usually the key step in determining the ends of the intron to be spliced out, and defining the ends of the exon to be retained.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] (The U nomenclature derives from their high uridine content).
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The U4,U5,U6 complex binds, and U6 replaces the U1 position.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The remaining complex then performs two transesterification reactions.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In the first transesterification, 5' end of the intron is cleaved from the upstream exon and joined to the branch site A by a 2',5'-phosphodiester linkage.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In the second transesterification, the 3' end of the intron is cleaved from the downstream exon, and the two exons are joined by a phosphodiester bond.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The intron is then released in lariat form and degraded.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Splicing is regulated by trans-acting proteins (repressors and activators) and corresponding cis-acting regulatory sites (silencers and enhancers) on the pre-mRNA.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] However, as part of the complexity of alternative splicing, it is noted that the effects of a splicing factor are frequently position-dependent.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] That is, a splicing factor that serves as a splicing activator when bound to an intronic enhancer element may serve as a repressor when bound to its splicing element in the context of an exon, and vice versa.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The secondary structure of the pre-mRNA transcript also plays a role in regulating splicing, such as by bringing together splicing elements or by masking a sequence that would otherwise serve as a binding element for a splicing factor.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Together, these elements form a "splicing code" that governs how splicing will occur under different cellular conditions.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] There are two major types of cis-acting RNA sequence elements present in pre-mRNAs and they have corresponding trans-acting RNA-binding proteins.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Splicing *silencers* are sites to which splicing repressor proteins bind, reducing the probability that a nearby site will be used as a splice junction.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] These can be located in the intron itself (intronic splicing silencers, ISS) or in a neighboring exon (exonic splicing silencers, ESS).
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] They vary in sequence, as well as in the types of proteins that bind to them.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The majority of splicing repressors are heterogeneous nuclear ribonucleoproteins (hnRNPs) such as hnRNPA1 and polypyrimidine tract-binding protein (PTB).
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Splicing *enhancers* are sites to which splicing activator proteins bind, increasing the probability that a nearby site will be used as a splice junction.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] These also may occur in the intron (intronic splicing enhancers, ISE) or exon (exonic splicing enhancers, ESE).
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Most of the activator proteins that bind to ISEs and ESEs are members of the SR protein family.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Such proteins contain RNA recognition motifs and arginine and serine-rich (RS) domains.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In general, the determinants of splicing work in an inter-dependent manner that depends on context, so that the rules governing how splicing is regulated form a splicing code.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The presence of a particular cis-acting RNA sequence element may increase the probability that a nearby site will be spliced in some cases, but decrease the probability in other cases, depending on context.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The context within which regulatory elements act includes cis-acting context that is established by the presence of other RNA sequence features, and trans-acting context that is established by cellular conditions.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] For example, some cis-acting RNA sequence elements influence splicing only if multiple elements are present in the same region so as to establish context.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] As another example, a cis-acting element can have opposite effects on splicing, depending on which proteins are expressed in the cell (e.g., neuronal versus non-neuronal PTB).
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The adaptive significance of splicing silencers and enhancers is attested by studies showing that there is strong selection in human genes against mutations that produce new silencers or disrupt existing enhancers.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Pre-mRNAs from the *Drosophila melanogaster* gene *dsx* contain 6 exons.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In males, exons 1, 2, 3, 5, and 6 are joined to form the mRNA, which encodes a transcriptional regulatory protein required for male development.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In females, exons 1, 2, 3, and 4 are joined, and a polyadenylation signal in exon 4 causes cleavage of the mRNA at that point.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The resulting mRNA is a transcriptional regulatory protein required for female development.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The intron upstream from exon 4 has a polypyrimidine tract that does not match the consensus sequence well, so that U2AF proteins bind poorly to it without assistance from splicing activators.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] This 3' splice acceptor site is therefore not used in males.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Females, however, produce the splicing activator Transformer (Tra) (see below).
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The SR protein Tra2 is produced in both sexes and binds to an ESE in exon 4; if Tra is present, it binds to Tra2 and, along with another SR protein, forms a complex that assists U2AF proteins in binding to the weak polypyrimidine tract.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] U2 is recruited to the associated branchpoint, and this leads to inclusion of exon 4 in the mRNA.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Pre-mRNAs of the *Transformer* (Tra) gene of *Drosophila melanogaster* undergo alternative splicing via the alternative acceptor site mode.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The gene Tra encodes a protein that is expressed only in females.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The primary transcript of this gene contains an intron with two possible acceptor sites.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In males, the upstream acceptor site is used.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] This causes a longer version of exon 2 to be included in the processed transcript, including an early stop codon.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The resulting mRNA encodes a truncated protein product that is inactive.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Females produce the master sex determination protein Sex lethal (Sxl).
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The Sxl protein is a splicing repressor that binds to an ISS in the RNA of the Tra transcript near the upstream acceptor site, preventing U2AF protein from binding to the polypyrimidine tract.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] This prevents the use of this junction, shifting the spliceosome binding to the downstream acceptor site.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Splicing at this point bypasses the stop codon, which is excised as part of the intron.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The resulting mRNA encodes an active Tra protein, which itself is a regulator of alternative splicing of other sex-related genes (see *dsx* above).
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Multiple isoforms of the Fas receptor protein are produced by alternative splicing.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Two normally occurring isoforms in humans are produced by an exon-skipping mechanism.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] An mRNA including exon 6 encodes the membrane-bound form of the Fas receptor, which promotes apoptosis, or programmed cell death.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Increased expression of Fas receptor in skin cells chronically exposed to the sun, and absence of expression in skin cancer cells, suggests that this mechanism may be important in elimination of pre-cancerous cells in humans.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] If exon 6 is skipped, the resulting mRNA encodes a soluble Fas protein that does not promote apoptosis.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The inclusion or skipping of the exon depends on two antagonistic proteins, TIA-1 and polypyrimidine tract-binding protein (PTB).
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] This mechanism is an example of exon definition in splicing.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] A spliceosome assembles on an intron, and the snRNP subunits fold the RNA so that the 5' and 3' ends of the intron are joined.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] However, recently studied examples such as this one show that there are also interactions between the ends of the exon.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In this particular case, these exon definition interactions are necessary to allow the binding of core splicing factors prior to assembly of the spliceosomes on the two flanking introns.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] HIV, the retrovirus that causes AIDS in humans, produces a single primary RNA transcript, which is alternatively spliced in multiple ways to produce over 40 different mRNAs.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Equilibrium among differentially spliced transcripts provides multiple mRNAs encoding different products that are required for viral multiplication.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] One of the differentially spliced transcripts contains the *tat* gene, in which exon 2 is a cassette exon that may be skipped or included.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The inclusion of tat exon 2 in the RNA is regulated by competition between the splicing repressor hnRNP A1 and the SR protein SC35.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Within exon 2 an exonic splicing silencer sequence (ESS) and an exonic splicing enhancer sequence (ESE) overlap.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] If A1 repressor protein binds to the ESS, it initiates cooperative binding of multiple A1 molecules, extending into the 5' donor site upstream of exon 2 and preventing the binding of the core splicing factor U2AF35 to the polypyrimidine tract.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] If SC35 binds to the ESE, it prevents A1 binding and maintains the 5' donor site in an accessible state for assembly of the spliceosome.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Competition between the activator and repressor ensures that both mRNA types (with and without exon 2) are produced.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Genuine alternative splicing occurs in both protein-coding genes and non-coding genes to produce multiple products (proteins or non-coding RNAs).
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] External information is needed in order to decide which product is made, given a DNA sequence and the initial transcript.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Since the methods of regulation are inherited, this provides novel ways for mutations to affect gene expression.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Alternative splicing may provide evolutionary flexibility.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] A single point mutation may cause a given exon to be occasionally excluded or included from a transcript during splicing, allowing production of a new protein isoform without loss of the original protein.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Studies have identified intrinsically disordered regions (see Intrinsically unstructured proteins) as enriched in the non-constitutive exons suggesting that protein isoforms may display functional diversity due to the alteration of functional modules within these regions.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Such functional diversity achieved by isoforms is reflected by their expression patterns and can be predicted by machine learning approaches.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Comparative studies indicate that alternative splicing preceded multicellularity in evolution, and suggest that this mechanism might have been co-opted to assist in the development of multicellular organisms.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Research based on the Human Genome Project and other genome sequencing has shown that humans have only about 30% more genes than the roundworm *Caenorhabditis elegans*, and only about twice as many as the fly *Drosophila melanogaster*.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] This finding led to speculation that the perceived greater complexity of humans, or vertebrates generally, might be due to higher rates of alternative splicing in humans than are found in invertebrates.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Another study, however, proposed that these results were an artifact of the different numbers of ESTs available for the various organisms.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] When they compared alternative splicing frequencies in random subsets of genes from each organism, the authors concluded that vertebrates do have higher rates of alternative splicing than invertebrates.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Changes in the RNA processing machinery may lead to mis-splicing of multiple transcripts, while single-nucleotide alterations in splice sites or cis-acting splicing regulatory sites may lead to differences in splicing of a single gene, and thus in the mRNA produced from a mutant gene's transcripts.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] A study in 2005 involving probabilistic analyses indicated that greater than 60% of human disease-causing mutations affect splicing rather than directly affecting coding sequences.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] A more recent study indicates that one-third of all hereditary diseases are likely to have a splicing component.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Regardless of exact percentage, a number of splicing-related diseases do exist.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] As described below, a prominent example of splicing-related diseases is cancer.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Abnormally spliced mRNAs are also found in a high proportion of cancerous cells.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Combined RNA-Seq and proteomics analyses have revealed striking differential expression of splice isoforms of key proteins in important cancer pathways.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] It is not always clear whether such aberrant patterns of splicing contribute to the cancerous growth, or are merely consequence of cellular abnormalities associated with cancer.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] For certain types of cancer, like in colorectal and prostate, the number of splicing errors per cancer has been shown to vary greatly between individual cancers, a phenomenon referred to as transcriptome instability.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Transcriptome instability has further been shown to correlate greatly with reduced expression level of splicing factor genes.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Mutation of *DNMT3A* has been demonstrated to contribute to hematologic malignancies, and that *DNMT3A*-mutated cell lines exhibit transcriptome instability as compared to their isogenic wildtype counterparts.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In fact, there is actually a reduction of alternative splicing in cancerous cells compared to normal ones, and the types of splicing differ; for instance, cancerous cells show higher levels of intron retention than normal cells, but lower levels of exon skipping.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Some of the differences in splicing in cancerous cells may be due to the high frequency of somatic mutations in splicing factor genes, and some may result from changes in phosphorylation of trans-acting splicing factors.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Others may be produced by changes in the relative amounts of splicing factors produced; for instance, breast cancer cells have been shown to have increased levels of the splicing factor SF2/ASF.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] One study found that a relatively small percentage (383 out of over 26000) of alternative splicing variants were significantly higher in frequency in tumor cells than normal cells, suggesting that there is a limited set of genes which, when mis-spliced, contribute to tumor development.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] It is believed however that the deleterious effects of mis-spliced transcripts are usually safeguarded and eliminated by a cellular posttranscriptional quality control mechanism termed nonsense-mediated mRNA decay [NMD].
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] One example of a specific splicing variant associated with cancers is in one of the human DNMT genes.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Three DNMT genes encode enzymes that add methyl groups to DNA, a modification that often has regulatory effects.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Several abnormally spliced DNMT3B mRNAs are found in tumors and cancer cell lines.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In two separate studies, expression of two of these abnormally spliced mRNAs in mammalian cells caused changes in the DNA methylation patterns in those cells.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Cells with one of the abnormal mRNAs also grew twice as fast as control cells, indicating a direct contribution to tumor development by this product.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Another example is the *Ron* (*MST1R*) proto-oncogene.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] An important property of cancerous cells is their ability to move and invade normal tissue.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Production of an abnormally spliced transcript of *Ron* has been found to be associated with increased levels of the SF2/ASF in breast cancer cells.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The abnormal isoform of the Ron protein encoded by this mRNA leads to cell motility.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Overexpression of a truncated splice variant of the FOSB gene – ΔFosB – in a specific population of neurons in the nucleus accumbens has been identified as the causal mechanism involved in the induction and maintenance of an addiction to drugs and natural rewards.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Recent provocative studies point to a key function of chromatin structure and histone modifications in alternative splicing regulation.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] These insights suggest that epigenetic regulation determines not only what parts of the genome are expressed but also how they are spliced.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Transcriptome-wide analysis of alternative splicing is typically performed by high-throughput RNA-sequencing.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Most commonly, by short-read sequencing, such as by Illumina instrumentation.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] But even more informative, by long-read sequencing, such as by Nanopore or PacBio instrumentation.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Transcriptome-wide analyses can for example be used to measure the amount of deviating alternative splicing, such as in a cancer cohort.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Deep sequencing technologies have been used to conduct genome-wide analyses of both unprocessed and processed mRNAs; thus providing insights into alternative splicing.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] For example, results from use of deep sequencing indicate that, in humans, an estimated 95% of transcripts from multiexon genes undergo alternative splicing, with a number of pre-mRNA transcripts spliced in a tissue-specific manner.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Functional genomics and computational approaches based on multiple instance learning have also been developed to integrate RNA-seq data to predict functions for alternatively spliced isoforms.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Deep sequencing has also aided in the *in vivo* detection of the transient lariats that are released during splicing, the determination of branch site sequences, and the large-scale mapping of branchpoints in human pre-mRNA transcripts.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] More historically, alternatively spliced transcripts have been found by comparing EST sequences, but this requires sequencing of very large numbers of ESTs.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Most EST libraries come from a very limited number of tissues, so tissue-specific splice variants are likely to be missed in any case.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] High-throughput approaches to investigate splicing have, however, been developed, such as: DNA microarray–based analyses, RNA-binding assays, and deep sequencing.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] These methods can be used to screen for polymorphisms or mutations in or around splicing elements that affect protein binding.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] When combined with splicing assays, including *in vivo* reporter gene assays, the functional effects of polymorphisms or mutations on the splicing of pre-mRNA transcripts can then be analyzed.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] In microarray analysis, arrays of DNA fragments representing individual exons (*e.g.* Affymetrix exon microarray) or exon/exon boundaries (*e.g.* arrays from ExonHit or Jivan) have been used.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The array is then probed with labeled cDNA from tissues of interest.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] The probe cDNAs bind to DNA from the exons that are included in mRNAs in their tissue of origin, or to DNA from the boundary where two exons have been joined.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] This can reveal the presence of particular alternatively spliced mRNAs.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] CLIP (Cross-linking and immunoprecipitation) uses UV radiation to link proteins to RNA molecules in a tissue during splicing.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] A trans-acting splicing regulatory protein of interest is then precipitated using specific antibodies.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] When the RNA attached to that protein is isolated and cloned, it reveals the target sequences for that protein.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Use of the MEGAshift method has provided insights into the regulation of alternative splicing by allowing for the identification of sequences in pre-mRNA transcripts surrounding alternatively spliced exons that mediate binding to different splicing factors, such as ASF/SF2 and PTB.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] This approach has also been used to aid in determining the relationship between RNA secondary structure and the binding of splicing factors.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Use of reporter assays makes it possible to find the splicing proteins involved in a specific alternative splicing event by constructing reporter genes that will express one of two different fluorescent proteins depending on the splicing reaction that occurs.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] This method has been used to isolate mutants affecting splicing and thus to identify novel splicing regulatory proteins inactivated in those mutants.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] Recent advancements in protein structure prediction have facilitated the development of new tools for genome annotation and alternative splicing analysis.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] For instance, isoform.io, a platform guided by protein structure predictions, has evaluated hundreds of thousands of isoforms of human protein-coding genes assembled from numerous RNA sequencing experiments across a variety of human tissues.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] This comprehensive analysis has led to the identification of numerous isoforms with more confidently predicted structure and potentially superior function compared to canonical isoforms in the latest human gene database.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] By integrating structural predictions with expression and evolutionary evidence, this approach has demonstrated the potential of protein structure prediction as a tool for refining the annotation of the human genome.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] There is a collection of alternative splicing databases.
[src:transcriptomics/alternative-splicing] These databases are useful for finding genes having pre-mRNAs undergoing alternative splicing and alternative splicing events or to study the functional impact of alternative splicing.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] A **DNA microarray** (also commonly known as a **DNA chip** or **biochip**) is a collection of microscopic DNA spots attached to a solid surface.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Scientists use DNA microarrays to measure the expression levels of large numbers of genes simultaneously or to genotype multiple regions of a genome.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Each DNA spot contains picomoles (10−12 moles) of a specific DNA sequence, known as *probes* (or *reporters* or *oligos*).
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] These can be a short section of a gene or other DNA element that are used to hybridize a cDNA or cRNA (also called anti-sense RNA) sample (called *target*) under high-stringency conditions.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Probe-target hybridization is usually detected and quantified by detection of fluorophore-, silver-, or chemiluminescence-labeled targets to determine relative abundance of nucleic acid sequences in the target.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The original nucleic acid arrays were macro arrays approximately 9 cm × 12 cm and the first computerized image based analysis was published in 1981.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] An example of its application is in SNPs arrays for polymorphisms in cardiovascular diseases, cancer, pathogens and GWAS analysis.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] It is also used for the identification of structural variations and the measurement of gene expression.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The core principle behind microarrays is hybridization between two DNA strands, the property of complementary nucleic acid sequences to specifically pair with each other by forming hydrogen bonds between complementary nucleotide base pairs.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] A high number of complementary base pairs in a nucleotide sequence means tighter non-covalent bonding between the two strands.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] After washing off non-specific bonding sequences, only strongly paired strands will remain hybridized.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Fluorescently labeled target sequences that bind to a probe sequence generate a signal that depends on the hybridization conditions (such as temperature), and washing after hybridization.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Total strength of the signal, from a spot (feature), depends upon the amount of target sample binding to the probes present on that spot.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Microarrays use relative quantitation in which the intensity of a feature is compared to the intensity of the same feature under a different condition, and the identity of the feature is known by its position.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] DNA microarrays can be used to detect DNA (as in comparative genomic hybridization), or detect RNA (most commonly as cDNA after reverse transcription) that may or may not be translated into proteins.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The process of measuring gene expression via cDNA is called expression analysis or expression profiling.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Specialised arrays tailored to particular crops are becoming increasingly popular in molecular breeding applications.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] In the future they could be used to screen seedlings at early stages to lower the number of unneeded seedlings tried out in breeding operations.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Microarrays can be manufactured in different ways, depending on the number of probes under examination, costs, customization requirements, and the type of scientific question being asked.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Arrays from commercial vendors may have as few as 10 probes or as many as 5 million or more micrometre-scale probes.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Microarrays can be fabricated using a variety of technologies, including printing with fine-pointed pins onto glass slides, photolithography using pre-made masks, photolithography using dynamic micromirror devices, ink-jet printing, or electrochemistry on microelectrode arrays.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] In *spotted microarrays*, the probes are oligonucleotides, cDNA or small fragments of PCR products that correspond to mRNAs.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The probes are synthesized prior to deposition on the array surface and are then "spotted" onto glass.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] A common approach utilizes an array of fine pins or needles controlled by a robotic arm that is dipped into wells containing DNA probes and then depositing each probe at designated locations on the array surface.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The resulting "grid" of probes represents the nucleic acid profiles of the prepared probes and is ready to receive complementary cDNA or cRNA "targets" derived from experimental or clinical samples.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] This technique is used by research scientists around the world to produce "in-house" printed microarrays in their own labs.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] These arrays may be easily customized for each experiment, because researchers can choose the probes and printing locations on the arrays, synthesize the probes in their own lab (or collaborating facility), and spot the arrays.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] They can then generate their own labeled samples for hybridization, hybridize the samples to the array, and finally scan the arrays with their own equipment.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] This provides a relatively low-cost microarray that may be customized for each study, and avoids the costs of purchasing often more expensive commercial arrays that may represent vast numbers of genes that are not of interest to the investigator.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Publications exist which indicate in-house spotted microarrays may not provide the same level of sensitivity compared to commercial oligonucleotide arrays, possibly owing to the small batch sizes and reduced printing efficiencies when compared to industrial manufactures of oligo arrays.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] In *oligonucleotide microarrays*, the probes are short sequences designed to match parts of the sequence of known or predicted open reading frames.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Although oligonucleotide probes are often used in "spotted" microarrays, the term "oligonucleotide array" most often refers to a specific technique of manufacturing.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Oligonucleotide arrays are produced by printing short oligonucleotide sequences designed to represent a single gene or family of gene splice-variants by synthesizing this sequence directly onto the array surface instead of depositing intact sequences.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] One technique used to produce oligonucleotide arrays include photolithographic synthesis (Affymetrix) on a silica substrate where light and light-sensitive masking agents are used to "build" a sequence one nucleotide at a time across the entire array.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Each applicable probe is selectively "unmasked" prior to bathing the array in a solution of a single nucleotide, then a masking reaction takes place and the next set of probes are unmasked in preparation for a different nucleotide exposure.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] After many repetitions, the sequences of every probe become fully constructed.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] More recently, Maskless Array Synthesis from NimbleGen Systems has combined flexibility with large numbers of probes.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Oligonucleotide microarrays often carry control probes designed to hybridize with RNA spike-ins.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The degree of hybridization between the spike-ins and the control probes is used to normalize the hybridization measurements for the target probes.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Although absolute levels of gene expression may be determined in the two-color array in rare instances, the relative differences in expression among different spots within a sample and between samples is the preferred method of data analysis for the two-color system.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Examples of providers for such microarrays includes Agilent with their Dual-Mode platform, Eppendorf with their DualChip platform for colorimetric Silverquant labeling, and TeleChem International with Arrayit.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] In *single-channel microarrays* or *one-color microarrays*, the arrays provide intensity data for each probe or probe set indicating a relative level of hybridization with the labeled target.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] However, they do not truly indicate abundance levels of a gene but rather relative abundance when compared to other samples or conditions when processed in the same experiment.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Each RNA molecule encounters protocol and batch-specific bias during amplification, labeling, and hybridization phases of the experiment making comparisons between genes for the same microarray uninformative.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The comparison of two conditions for the same gene requires two separate single-dye hybridizations.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Several popular single-channel systems are the Affymetrix "Gene Chip", Illumina "Bead Chip", Agilent single-channel arrays, the Applied Microarrays "CodeLink" arrays, and the Eppendorf "DualChip & Silverquant".
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Another benefit is that data are more easily compared to arrays from different experiments as long as batch effects have been accounted for.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] One channel microarray may be the only choice in some situations.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Suppose i samples need to be compared: then the number of experiments required using the two channel arrays quickly becomes unfeasible, unless a sample is used as a reference.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] This is an example of a **DNA microarray experiment** which includes details for a particular case to better explain DNA microarray experiments, while listing modifications for RNA or other alternative experiments.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The nucleic acid of interest is purified: this can be RNA for expression profiling, DNA for comparative hybridization, or DNA/RNA bound to a particular protein which is immunoprecipitated (ChIP-on-chip) for epigenetic or regulation studies.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] In this example total RNA is isolated (both nuclear and cytoplasmic) by guanidinium thiocyanate-phenol-chloroform extraction (e.g.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Trizol) which isolates most RNA (whereas column methods have a cut off of 200 nucleotides) and if done correctly has a better purity.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The purified RNA is analysed for quality (by capillary electrophoresis) and quantity (for example, by using a NanoDrop or NanoPhotometer spectrometer).
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] If the material is of acceptable quality and sufficient quantity is present (e.g., >1μg, although the required amount varies by microarray platform), the experiment can proceed.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The labeled product is generated via reverse transcription and followed by an optional PCR amplification.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The RNA is reverse transcribed with either polyT primers (which amplify only mRNA) or random primers (which amplify all RNA, most of which is rRNA). miRNA microarrays ligate an oligonucleotide to the purified small RNA (isolated with a fractionator), which is then reverse transcribed and amplified.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The labeled samples are then mixed with a proprietary hybridization solution which can consist of SDS, SSC, dextran sulfate, a blocking agent (such as Cot-1 DNA, salmon sperm DNA, calf thymus DNA, PolyA, or PolyT), Denhardt's solution, or formamine.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The mixture is denatured and added to the pinholes of the microarray.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The holes are sealed and the microarray hybridized, either in a hyb oven, where the microarray is mixed by rotation, or in a mixer, where the microarray is mixed by alternating pressure at the pinholes.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] After an overnight hybridization, all nonspecific binding is washed off (SDS and SSC).
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The microarray is dried and scanned by a machine that uses a laser to excite the dye and measures the emission levels with a detector.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The image is gridded with a template and the intensities of each feature (composed of several pixels) is quantified.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The raw data is normalized; the simplest normalization method is to subtract background intensity and scale so that the total intensities of the features of the two channels are equal, or to use the intensity of a reference gene to calculate the t-value for all of the intensities.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] More sophisticated methods include z-ratio, loess and lowess regression and RMA (robust multichip analysis) for Affymetrix chips (single-channel, silicon chip, *in situ* synthesized short oligonucleotides).
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Due to the biological complexity of gene expression, the considerations of experimental design that are discussed in the expression profiling article are of critical importance if statistically and biologically valid conclusions are to be drawn from the data.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] There are three main elements to consider when designing a microarray experiment.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] First, replication of the biological samples is essential for drawing conclusions from the experiment.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Second, technical replicates (e.g. two RNA samples obtained from each experimental unit) may help to quantitate precision.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The biological replicates include independent RNA extractions.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Technical replicates may be two aliquots of the same extraction.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Third, spots of each cDNA clone or oligonucleotide are present as replicates (at least duplicates) on the microarray slide, to provide a measure of technical precision in each hybridization.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] It is critical that information about the sample preparation and handling is discussed, in order to help identify the independent units in the experiment and to avoid inflated estimates of statistical significance.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Microarray data is difficult to exchange due to the lack of standardization in platform fabrication, assay protocols, and analysis methods.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] This presents an interoperability problem in bioinformatics.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] For example, the "Minimum Information About a Microarray Experiment" (MIAME) checklist helps define the level of detail that should exist and is being adopted by many journals as a requirement for the submission of papers incorporating microarray results.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] But MIAME does not describe the format for the information, so while many formats can support the MIAME requirements, as of 2007 no format permits verification of complete semantic compliance.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The "MicroArray Quality Control (MAQC) Project" is being conducted by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) to develop standards and quality control metrics which will eventually allow the use of MicroArray data in drug discovery, clinical practice and regulatory decision-making.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The MGED Society has developed standards for the representation of gene expression experiment results and relevant annotations.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Microarray data sets are commonly very large, and analytical precision is influenced by a number of variables.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Statistical challenges include taking into account effects of background noise and appropriate normalization of the data.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Normalization methods may be suited to specific platforms and, in the case of commercial platforms, the analysis may be proprietary.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Microarray data may require further processing aimed at reducing the dimensionality of the data to aid comprehension and more focused analysis.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Other methods permit analysis of data consisting of a low number of biological or technical replicates; for example, the Local Pooled Error (LPE) test pools standard deviations of genes with similar expression levels in an effort to compensate for insufficient replication.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The relation between a probe and the mRNA that it is expected to detect is not trivial.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Some mRNAs may cross-hybridize probes in the array that are supposed to detect another mRNA.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] In addition, mRNAs may experience amplification bias that is sequence or molecule-specific.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Thirdly, probes that are designed to detect the mRNA of a particular gene may be relying on genomic EST information that is incorrectly associated with that gene.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Microarray data was found to be more useful when compared to other similar datasets.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] The sheer volume of data, specialized formats (such as MIAME), and curation efforts associated with the datasets require specialized databases to store the data.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] A number of open-source data warehousing solutions, such as InterMine and BioMart, have been created for the specific purpose of integrating diverse biological datasets, and also support analysis.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Advances in massively parallel sequencing has led to the development of RNA-Seq technology, that enables a whole transcriptome shotgun approach to characterize and quantify gene expression.
[src:transcriptomics/dna-microarray] Unlike microarrays, which need a reference genome and transcriptome to be available before the microarray itself can be designed, RNA-Seq can also be used for new model organisms whose genome has not been sequenced yet.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] In genetics, an **expressed sequence tag** (**EST**) is a short sub-sequence of a cDNA sequence.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] ESTs may be used to identify gene transcripts, and were instrumental in gene discovery and in gene-sequence determination.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] The identification of ESTs has proceeded rapidly, with approximately 74.2 million ESTs now available in public databases (e.g.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] EST approaches have largely been superseded by whole genome and transcriptome sequencing and metagenome sequencing.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] An EST results from one-shot sequencing of a cloned cDNA.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] The cDNAs used for EST generation are typically individual clones from a cDNA library.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] The resulting sequence is a relatively low-quality fragment whose length is limited by current technology to approximately 500 to 800 nucleotides.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] Because these clones consist of DNA that is complementary to mRNA, the ESTs represent portions of expressed genes.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] They may be represented in databases as either cDNA/mRNA sequence or as the reverse complement of the mRNA, the template strand.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] One can map ESTs to specific chromosome locations using physical mapping techniques, such as radiation hybrid mapping, HAPPY mapping, or FISH.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] Alternatively, if the genome of the organism that originated the EST has been sequenced, one can align the EST sequence to that genome using a computer.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] The current understanding of the human set of genes (as of 2006) includes the existence of thousands of genes based solely on EST evidence.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] In this respect, ESTs have become a tool to refine the predicted transcripts for those genes, which leads to the prediction of their protein products and ultimately of their function.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] Moreover, the situation in which those ESTs are obtained (tissue, organ, disease state - e.g. cancer) gives information on the conditions in which the corresponding gene is acting.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] ESTs contain enough information to permit the design of precise probes for DNA microarrays that then can be used to determine gene expression profiles.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] Some authors use the term "EST" to describe genes for which little or no further information exists besides the tag.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] In 1979, teams at Harvard and Caltech extended the basic idea of making DNA copies of mRNAs in vitro to amplifying a library of such in bacterial plasmids.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] In 1982, the idea of selecting random or semi-random clones from such a cDNA library for sequencing was explored by Greg Sutcliffe and coworkers.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] In 1983, Putney et al. sequenced 178 clones from a rabbit muscle cDNA library.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] In 1991, Adams and co-workers coined the term EST and initiated more systematic sequencing as a project (starting with 600 brain cDNAs).
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] The dbEST is a division of Genbank established in 1992.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] As for GenBank, data in dbEST is directly submitted by laboratories worldwide and is not curated.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] Because of the way ESTs are sequenced, many distinct expressed sequence tags are often partial sequences that correspond to the same mRNA of an organism.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] In an effort to reduce the number of expressed sequence tags for downstream gene discovery analyses, several groups assembled expressed sequence tags into EST contigs.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] Constructing EST contigs is not trivial and may yield artifacts (contigs that contain two distinct gene products).
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] When the complete genome sequence of an organism is available and transcripts are annotated, it is possible to bypass contig assembly and directly match transcripts with ESTs.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] This approach is used in the TissueInfo system (see below) and makes it easy to link annotations in the genomic database to tissue information provided by EST data.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] High-throughput analyses of ESTs often encounter similar data management challenges.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] A first challenge is that tissue provenance of EST libraries is described in plain English in dbEST.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] This makes it difficult to write programs that can unambiguously determine that two EST libraries were sequenced from the same tissue.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] Similarly, disease conditions for the tissue are not annotated in a computationally friendly manner.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] For instance, cancer origin of a library is often mixed with the tissue name (e.g., the tissue name "glioblastoma" indicates that the EST library was sequenced from brain tissue and the disease condition is cancer).
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] With the notable exception of cancer, the disease condition is often not recorded in dbEST entries.
[src:transcriptomics/expressed-sequence-tag] The TissueInfo project was started in 2000 to help with these challenges.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] A **spliceosome** is a large ribonucleoprotein (RNP) complex found primarily within the nucleus of eukaryotic cells.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The spliceosome is assembled from small nuclear RNAs (snRNA) and numerous proteins.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Small nuclear RNA (snRNA) molecules bind to specific proteins to form a small nuclear ribonucleoprotein complex (snRNP, pronounced "snurps"), which in turn combines with other snRNPs to form a large ribonucleoprotein complex called a spliceosome.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The spliceosome removes introns from a transcribed pre-mRNA, a type of primary transcript.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] This process is generally referred to as splicing.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] An analogy is a film editor, who selectively cuts out irrelevant or incorrect material (equivalent to the introns) from the initial film and sends the cleaned-up version to the director for the final cut.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] However, sometimes the RNA within the intron acts as a ribozyme, splicing itself without the use of a spliceosome or any enzymes.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] In 1977, work by the Sharp and Roberts labs revealed that genes of higher organisms are "split" or present in several distinct segments along the DNA molecule.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The coding regions of the gene are separated by non-coding DNA that is not involved in protein expression.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The split gene structure was found when adenoviral mRNAs were hybridized to endonuclease cleavage fragments of single stranded viral DNA.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] It was observed that the mRNAs of the mRNA-DNA hybrids contained 5' and 3' tails of non-hydrogen bonded regions.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] When larger fragments of viral DNAs were used, forked structures of looped out DNA were observed when hybridized to the viral mRNAs.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] It was realised that the looped out regions, the introns, are excised from the precursor mRNAs in a process Sharp named "splicing".
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The split gene structure was subsequently found to be common to most eukaryotic genes.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Roberts were awarded the Nobel Prize in Medicine 1998 for the discovery of introns and the splicing process.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Each spliceosome is composed of five small nuclear RNAs (snRNA) and a range of associated protein factors.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] When these small RNAs are combined with the protein factors, they make RNA-protein complexes called snRNPs (small nuclear ribonucleoproteins, pronounced "snurps").
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The snRNAs that make up the major spliceosome are named U1, U2, U4, U5, and U6, so-called because they are rich in uridine, and participate in several RNA-RNA and RNA-protein interactions.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The assembly of the spliceosome occurs on each pre-mRNA (also known as heterogeneous nuclear RNA, hn-RNA) at each exon:intron junction.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The pre-mRNA introns contains specific sequence elements that are recognized and utilized during spliceosome assembly.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] These include the 5' end splice site, the branch point sequence, the polypyrimidine tract, and the 3' end splice site.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The spliceosome catalyzes the removal of introns, and the ligation of the flanking exons.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Introns typically have a GU nucleotide sequence at the 5' end splice site, and an AG at the 3' end splice site.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The 3' splice site can be further defined by a variable length of polypyrimidines, called the polypyrimidine tract (PPT), which serves the dual function of recruiting factors to the 3' splice site and possibly recruiting factors to the branch point sequence (BPS).
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The BPS contains the conserved adenosine required for the first step of splicing.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Many proteins exhibit a zinc-binding motif, which underscores the importance of zinc in the splicing mechanism.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The first molecular-resolution reconstruction of U4/U6.U5 triple small nuclear ribonucleoprotein (tri-snRNP) complex was reported in 2016.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Cryo-EM has been applied extensively by Shi et al. to elucidate the near-/atomic structure of spliceosome in both yeast and humans.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The molecular framework of spliceosome at near-atomic-resolution demonstrates Spp42 component of U5 snRNP forms a central scaffold and anchors the catalytic center in yeast.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The atomic structure of the human spliceosome illustrates the step II component Slu7 adopts an extended structure, poised for selection of the 3'-splice site.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] All five metals (assigned as Mg2+) in the yeast complex are preserved in the human complex.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Alternative splicing (the re-combination of different exons) is a major source of genetic diversity in eukaryotes.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Splice variants have been used to account for the relatively small number of protein coding genes in the human genome, currently estimated at around 20,000.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] One particular Drosophila gene, Dscam, has been speculated to be alternatively spliced into 38,000 different mRNAs, assuming all of its exons can splice independently of each other.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Pre-mRNA splicing factors were originally found to be concentrated in nuclear bodies known as nuclear speckles.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] It was originally postulated that nuclear speckles are either sites of mRNA splicing or storage sites of mRNA splicing factors.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] It is now understood that nuclear speckles help concentrate splicing factors near genes that are physically located close to them.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Genes located farther from speckles can still be transcribed and spliced, but their splicing is less efficient compared to those closer to speckles.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] RNA splicing is a biochemical reaction, and like all biochemical reactions, its rate depends on the concentration of enzymes and substrates.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] In this case, the enzymes are the spliceosomes, and the substrates are the pre-mRNAs.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] By varying the concentration of spliceosomes and pre-mRNAs based on their proximity to nuclear speckles, cells could potentially regulate the efficiency of splicing.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The model for formation of the spliceosome active site involves an ordered, stepwise assembly of discrete snRNP particles on the pre-mRNA substrate.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The first recognition of pre-mRNAs involves U1 snRNP binding to the 5' end splice site of the pre-mRNA and other non-snRNP associated factors to form the commitment complex, or early (E) complex in mammals.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The commitment complex is an ATP-independent complex that commits the pre-mRNA to the splicing pathway.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] U2 snRNP is recruited to the branch region through interactions with the E complex component U2AF (U2 snRNP auxiliary factor) and possibly U1 snRNP.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] In an ATP-dependent reaction, U2 snRNP becomes tightly associated with the branch point sequence (BPS) to form complex A.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] A duplex formed between U2 snRNP and the pre-mRNA branch region bulges out the branch adenosine specifying it as the nucleophile for the first transesterification.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The presence of a pseudouridine residue in U2 snRNA, nearly opposite of the branch site, results in an altered conformation of the RNA-RNA duplex upon the U2 snRNP binding.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Specifically, the altered structure of the duplex induced by the pseudouridine places the 2' OH of the bulged adenosine in a favorable position for the first step of splicing.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The U4/U5/U6 tri-snRNP (see Figure 1) is recruited to the assembling spliceosome to form complex B, and following several rearrangements, complex C is activated for catalysis.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] It is unclear how the tri-snRNP is recruited to complex A, but this process may be mediated through protein-protein interactions and/or base pairing interactions between U2 snRNA and U6 snRNA.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The U5 snRNP interacts with sequences at the 5' and 3' splice sites via the invariant loop of U5 snRNA and U5 protein components interact with the 3' splice site region.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Upon recruitment of the tri-snRNP, several RNA-RNA rearrangements precede the first catalytic step and further rearrangements occur in the catalytically active spliceosome.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Several of the RNA-RNA interactions are mutually exclusive; however, it is not known what triggers these interactions, nor the order of these rearrangements.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The first rearrangement is probably the displacement of U1 snRNP from the 5' splice site and formation of a U6 snRNA interaction.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] It is known that U1 snRNP is only weakly associated with fully formed spliceosomes, and U1 snRNP is inhibitory to the formation of a U6-5' splice site interaction on a model of substrate oligonucleotide containing a short 5' exon and 5' splice site.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Binding of U2 snRNP to the branch point sequence (BPS) is one example of an RNA-RNA interaction displacing a protein-RNA interaction.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Upon recruitment of U2 snRNP, the branch binding protein SF1 in the commitment complex is displaced since the binding site of U2 snRNA and SF1 are mutually exclusive events.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Within the U2 snRNA, there are other mutually exclusive rearrangements that occur between competing conformations.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] For example, in the active form, stem loop IIa is favored; in the inactive form a mutually exclusive interaction between the loop and a downstream sequence predominates.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] It is unclear how U4 is displaced from U6 snRNA, although RNA has been implicated in spliceosome assembly, and may function to unwind U4/U6 and promote the formation of a U2/U6 snRNA interaction.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The interactions of U4/U6 stem loops I and II dissociate and the freed stem loop II region of U6 folds on itself to form an intramolecular stem loop and U4 is no longer required in further spliceosome assembly.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The freed stem loop I region of U6 base pairs with U2 snRNA forming the U2/U6 helix I.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] However, the helix I structure is mutually exclusive with the 3' half of an internal 5' stem loop region of U2 snRNA.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] Some eukaryotes have a second spliceosome, the so-called minor spliceosome.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] A group of less abundant snRNAs, U11, U12, U4atac, and U6atac, together with U5, are subunits of the minor spliceosome that splices a rare class of pre-mRNA introns, denoted U12-type.
[src:transcriptomics/spliceosome] The minor spliceosome is located in the nucleus like its major counterpart, though there are exceptions in some specialised cells including anucleate platelets and the dendroplasm (dendrite cytoplasm) of neuronal cells.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The **transcriptome** is the set of all RNA molecules (transcripts) in a cell or a population of cells.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] It includes all of the functional RNA molecules and all other transcripts that may arise by spurious transcription or transcription of non-functional regions such as pseudogenes or virus fragments.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] A major goal of modern molecular biology is to determine which transcripts are functional and which ones are junk RNA.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The term *transcriptome* is a portmanteau of the words *transcript* and *genome*; it is associated with the process of transcript production during the biological process of transcription.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The functional part of the transcriptome is dynamic — it changes with cell type, developmental stage, environment, and stimuli — and therefore represents the active gene expression state rather than the static DNA sequence (genome).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Eukaryotic transcriptomes tend to be more complex than bacterial transcriptomes and the transcriptomes of multicellular eukaryotes are even more complex than those of unicellular eukaryotes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The word *transcriptome* is a portmanteau of the words *transcript* and *genome*.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] It appeared along with other neologisms formed using the suffixes *-ome* and *-omics* to denote all studies conducted on a genome-wide scale in the fields of life sciences and technology.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] As such, transcriptome and transcriptomics were one of the first words to emerge along with genome and proteome.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The first study to present a case of a collection of a cDNA library for silk moth mRNA was published in 1979.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The first seminal study to mention and investigate the transcriptome of an organism was published in 1997 and it described 60,633 transcripts expressed in *S. cerevisiae* using serial analysis of gene expression (SAGE).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] With the rise of high-throughput technologies and bioinformatics and the subsequent increased computational power, it became increasingly efficient and easy to characterize and analyze enormous amount of data.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Attempts to characterize the transcriptome became more prominent with the advent of automated DNA sequencing during the 1980s.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] During the 1990s, expressed sequence tag sequencing was used to identify genes and their fragments.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] This was followed by techniques such as serial analysis of gene expression (SAGE), cap analysis of gene expression (CAGE), and massively parallel signature sequencing (MPSS).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The transcriptome encompasses all the ribonucleic acid (RNA) transcripts present in a given organism or experimental sample.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The functional component of the transcriptome includes RNAs that carry genetic information that is responsible for the process of converting DNA into an organism's phenotype.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] A gene gives rise to a single-stranded RNA molecule through a molecular process known as transcription; this RNA is complementary to the strand of DNA it originated from.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The enzyme RNA polymerase attaches to the template DNA strand and catalyzes the addition of ribonucleotides to the 3' end of the growing sequence of the RNA transcript.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] In order to initiate its function, RNA polymerase needs to recognize a promoter sequence, located near the transcription start site that defines the beginning of the gene.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] This process is usually mediated and regulated by transcription factors.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Transcription ends at a terminator site that defines the other end of the gene.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The terminator site is often identified by termination sequences.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Almost all functional transcripts are derived from known genes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The only exceptions are a small number of transcripts that might play a direct role in regulating gene expression near the prompters of known genes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Genes occupy most of prokaryotic genomes so most of their genomes are transcribed.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Many eukaryotic genomes are very large and known genes may take up only a fraction of the genome.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] In mammals, for example, known genes only account for 40-50% of the genome.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Nevertheless, identified transcripts often map to a much larger fraction of the genome suggesting that the transcriptome contains spurious transcripts that do not come from genes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Some of these transcripts are known to be non-functional because they map to transcribed pseudogenes or degenerative transposons and viruses.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Others map to unidentified regions of the genome that may be junk DNA.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Spurious transcription is very common in eukaryotes, especially those with large genomes that might contain a lot of junk DNA.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Some scientists claim that if a transcript has not been assigned to a known gene then the default assumption must be that it is junk RNA until it has been shown to be functional.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] This would mean that much of the transcriptome in species with large genomes is probably junk RNA.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The transcriptome includes the transcripts of protein-coding genes (mRNA plus introns) as well as the transcripts of non-coding genes (functional RNAs plus introns).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] In the human genome, all genes get transcribed into RNA because that's how the molecular gene is defined.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] (See Gene.) The transcriptome consists of coding regions of mRNA plus non-coding untranslated regions (UTRs), introns, non-coding RNAs, and spurious non-functional transcripts.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Several factors render the content of the transcriptome difficult to establish.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] These include alternative splicing, RNA editing and alternative transcription among others.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Additionally, transcriptome techniques are capable of capturing transcription occurring in a sample at a specific time point, although the content of the transcriptome can change during differentiation.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The term can be applied to the total set of transcripts in a given organism, or to the specific subset of transcripts present in a particular cell type.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Unlike the genome, which is roughly fixed for a given cell line (excluding mutations), the transcriptome can vary with external environmental conditions.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Because it includes all mRNA transcripts in the cell, the transcriptome reflects the genes that are being actively expressed at any given time, with the exception of mRNA degradation phenomena such as transcriptional attenuation.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The study of transcriptomics, (which includes expression profiling, splice variant analysis etc.), examines the expression level of RNAs in a given cell population, often focusing on mRNA, but sometimes including others such as tRNAs and sRNAs.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Transcriptomics is the quantitative science that encompasses the assignment of a list of strings ("reads") to the object ("transcripts" in the genome).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] To calculate the expression strength, the density of reads corresponding to each object is counted.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Initially, transcriptomes were analyzed and studied using expressed sequence tags libraries and serial and cap analysis of gene expression (SAGE).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Currently, the two main transcriptomics techniques include DNA microarrays and RNA-Seq.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Both techniques require RNA isolation through RNA extraction techniques, followed by its separation from other cellular components and enrichment of mRNA.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] There are two general methods of inferring transcriptome sequences.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] One approach maps sequence reads onto a reference genome, either of the organism itself (whose transcriptome is being studied) or of a closely related species.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The other approach, *de novo* transcriptome assembly, uses software to infer transcripts directly from short sequence reads and is used in organisms with genomes that are not sequenced.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The first transcriptome studies were based on microarray techniques (also known as DNA chips).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Microarrays consist of thin glass layers with spots on which oligonucleotides, known as "probes" are arrayed; each spot contains a known DNA sequence.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] When performing microarray analyses, mRNA is collected from a control and an experimental sample, the latter usually representative of a disease.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The RNA of interest is converted to cDNA to increase its stability and marked with fluorophores of two colors, usually green and red, for the two groups.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The cDNA is spread onto the surface of the microarray where it hybridizes with oligonucleotides on the chip and a laser is used to scan.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The fluorescence intensity on each spot of the microarray corresponds to the level of gene expression and based on the color of the fluorophores selected, it can be determined which of the samples exhibits higher levels of the mRNA of interest.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] One microarray usually contains enough oligonucleotides to represent all known genes; however, data obtained using microarrays does not provide information about unknown genes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] During the 2010s, microarrays were almost completely replaced by next-generation techniques that are based on DNA sequencing.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] RNA sequencing is a next-generation sequencing technology; as such it requires only a small amount of RNA and no previous knowledge of the genome.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] It allows for both qualitative and quantitative analysis of RNA transcripts, the former allowing discovery of new transcripts and the latter a measure of relative quantities for transcripts in a sample.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The three main steps of sequencing transcriptomes of any biological samples include RNA purification, the synthesis of an RNA or cDNA library and sequencing the library.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The RNA purification process is different for short and long RNAs.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] This step is usually followed by an assessment of RNA quality, with the purpose of avoiding contaminants such as DNA or technical contaminants related to sample processing.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] RNA quality is measured using UV spectrometry with an absorbance peak of 260 nm.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] RNA integrity can also be analyzed quantitatively comparing the ratio and intensity of 28S RNA to 18S RNA reported in the RNA Integrity Number (RIN) score.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Since mRNA is the species of interest and it represents only 3% of its total content, the RNA sample should be treated to remove rRNA and tRNA and tissue-specific RNA transcripts.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The step of library preparation with the aim of producing short cDNA fragments, begins with RNA fragmentation to transcripts in length between 50 and 300 base pairs.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Fragmentation can be enzymatic (RNA endonucleases), chemical (trismagnesium salt buffer, chemical hydrolysis) or mechanical (sonication, nebulisation).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Reverse transcription is used to convert the RNA templates into cDNA and three priming methods can be used to achieve it, including oligo-DT, using random primers or ligating special adaptor oligos.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Transcription can also be studied at the level of individual cells by single-cell transcriptomics.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNA-seq) is a recently developed technique that allows the analysis of the transcriptome of single cells, including bacteria.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] With single-cell transcriptomics, subpopulations of cell types that constitute the tissue of interest are also taken into consideration.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] This approach allows one to identify whether changes in experimental samples are due to phenotypic cellular changes as opposed to proliferation, with which a specific cell type might be overexpressed in the sample.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Additionally, when assessing cellular progression through differentiation, average expression profiles are only able to order cells by time rather than their stage of development and are consequently unable to show trends in gene expression levels specific to certain stages.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Single-cell transcriptomic techniques have been used to characterize rare cell populations such as circulating tumor cells, cancer stem cells in solid tumors, and embryonic stem cells (ESCs) in mammalian blastocysts.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Although there are no standardized techniques for single-cell transcriptomics, several steps need to be undertaken.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The first step includes cell isolation, which can be performed using low- and high-throughput techniques.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] This is followed by a qPCR step and then single-cell RNAseq where the RNA of interest is converted into cDNA.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Newer developments in single-cell transcriptomics allow for tissue and sub-cellular localization preservation through cryo-sectioning thin slices of tissues and sequencing the transcriptome in each slice.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Another technique allows the visualization of single transcripts under a microscope while preserving the spatial information of each individual cell where they are expressed.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] A number of organism-specific transcriptome databases have been constructed and annotated to aid in the identification of genes that are differentially expressed in distinct cell populations.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] RNA-seq is emerging (2013) as the method of choice for measuring transcriptomes of organisms, though the older technique of DNA microarrays is still used.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] RNA-seq measures the transcription of a specific gene by converting long RNAs into a library of cDNA fragments.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The cDNA fragments are then sequenced using high-throughput sequencing technology and aligned to a reference genome or transcriptome which is then used to create an expression profile of the genes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The number of protein-coding RNA sequences expression by each organ varies significantly between the organs, but also depends on the definitions and methodology used.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] In general, brain, testes, lymphatic system show the highest activity, and endometrium, gallbladder, seminal vesicle and smooth muscle show the lowest.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Analysis of the transcriptomes of human oocytes and embryos is used to understand the molecular mechanisms and signaling pathways controlling early embryonic development, and could theoretically be a powerful tool in making proper embryo selection in in vitro fertilisation.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Analyses of the transcriptome content of the placenta in the first-trimester of pregnancy in *in vitro* fertilization and embryo transfer (IVT-ET) revealed differences in genetic expression which are associated with higher frequency of adverse perinatal outcomes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Such insight can be used to optimize the practice.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Transcriptome analyses can also be used to optimize cryopreservation of oocytes, by lowering injuries associated with the process.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Transcriptomics is an emerging and continually growing field in biomarker discovery for use in assessing the safety of drugs or chemical risk assessment.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Transcriptomes may also be used to infer phylogenetic relationships among individuals or to detect evolutionary patterns of transcriptome conservation.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Transcriptome analyses were used to discover the incidence of antisense transcription, their role in gene expression through interaction with surrounding genes and their abundance in different chromosomes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] RNA-seq was also used to show how RNA isoforms, transcripts stemming from the same gene but with different structures, can produce complex phenotypes from limited genomes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Transcriptome analysis have been used to study the evolution and diversification process of plant species.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] In 2014, the 1000 Plant Genomes Project was completed in which the transcriptomes of 1,124 plant species from the families viridiplantae, glaucophyta and rhodophyta were sequenced.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The protein coding sequences were subsequently compared to infer phylogenetic relationships between plants and to characterize the time of their diversification in the process of evolution.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Transcriptome studies have been used to characterize and quantify gene expression in mature pollen.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Genes involved in cell wall metabolism and cytoskeleton were found to be overexpressed.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Transcriptome approaches also allowed to track changes in gene expression through different developmental stages of pollen, ranging from microspore to mature pollen grains; additionally such stages could be compared across species of different plants including *Arabidopsis*, rice and tobacco.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Similar to other -ome based technologies, analysis of the transcriptome allows for an unbiased approach when validating hypotheses experimentally.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] This approach also allows for the discovery of novel mediators in signaling pathways.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] As with other -omics based technologies, the transcriptome can be analyzed within the scope of a multiomics approach.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] It is complementary to metabolomics but contrary to proteomics, a direct association between a transcript and metabolite cannot be established.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] There are several -ome fields that can be seen as subcategories of the transcriptome.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The exome differs from the transcriptome in that it includes only those RNA molecules found in a specified cell population, and usually includes the amount or concentration of each RNA molecule in addition to the molecular identities.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Additionally, the transcriptome also differs from the translatome, which is the set of RNAs undergoing translation.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The term meiome is used in functional genomics to describe the meiotic transcriptome or the set of RNA transcripts produced during the process of meiosis.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Meiosis is a key feature of sexually reproducing eukaryotes, and involves the pairing of homologous chromosome, synapse and recombination.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Since meiosis in most organisms occurs in a short time period, meiotic transcript profiling is difficult due to the challenge of isolation (or enrichment) of meiotic cells (meiocytes).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] As with transcriptome analyses, the meiome can be studied at a whole-genome level using large-scale transcriptomic techniques.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The meiome has been well-characterized in mammal and yeast systems and somewhat less extensively characterized in plants.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The thanatotranscriptome consists of all RNA transcripts that continue to be expressed or that start getting re-expressed in internal organs of a dead body 24–48 hours following death.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Some genes include those that are inhibited after fetal development.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] If the thanatotranscriptome is related to the process of programmed cell death (apoptosis), it can be referred to as the apoptotic thanatotranscriptome.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Analyses of the thanatotranscriptome are used in forensic medicine.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] eQTL mapping can be used to complement genomics with transcriptomics; genetic variants at DNA level and gene expression measures at RNA level.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] The transcriptome can be seen as a subset of the proteome, that is, the entire set of proteins expressed by a genome.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] However, the analysis of relative mRNA expression levels can be complicated by the fact that relatively small changes in mRNA expression can produce large changes in the total amount of the corresponding protein present in the cell.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] One analysis method, known as gene set enrichment analysis, identifies coregulated gene networks rather than individual genes that are up- or down-regulated in different cell populations.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptome] Although microarray studies can reveal the relative amounts of different mRNAs in the cell, levels of mRNA are not directly proportional to the expression level of the proteins they code for.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The first attempts to study whole transcriptomes began in the early 1990s.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Subsequent technological advances since the late 1990s have repeatedly transformed the field and made transcriptomics a widespread discipline in biological sciences.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] There are two key contemporary techniques in the field: microarrays, which quantify a set of predetermined sequences, and RNA-Seq, which uses high-throughput sequencing to record all transcripts.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] As the technology improved, the volume of data produced by each transcriptome experiment increased.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] As a result, data analysis methods have steadily been adapted to more accurately and efficiently analyse increasingly large volumes of data.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptome databases have consequently been growing bigger and more useful as transcriptomes continue to be collected and shared by researchers.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] It would be almost impossible to interpret the information contained in a transcriptome without the knowledge of previous experiments.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Measuring the expression of an organism's genes in different tissues or conditions, or at different times, gives information on how genes are regulated and reveals details of an organism's biology.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] It can also be used to infer the functions of previously unannotated genes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptome analysis has enabled greater insight into gene expression changes in different organisms and has been instrumental in the understanding of human disease.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] An analysis of gene expression in its entirety allows detection of broad coordinated trends which cannot be discerned by more targeted assays.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomics has been characterised by the development of new techniques which have redefined what is possible every decade or so and rendered previous technologies obsolete.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The first attempt at capturing a partial human transcriptome was published in 1991 and reported 609 mRNA sequences from the human brain.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] In 2008, two human transcriptomes, composed of millions of transcript-derived sequences covering 16,000 genes, were published, and by 2015 transcriptomes had been published for hundreds of individuals.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomes of different disease states, tissues, or even single cells are now routinely generated.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] This explosion in transcriptomics has been driven by the rapid development of new technologies with improved sensitivity and economy.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Studies of individual transcripts were being performed several decades before any transcriptomics approaches were available.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Libraries of silkmoth mRNA transcripts were collected and converted to complementary DNA (cDNA) for storage using reverse transcriptase in the late 1970s.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] In the 1980s, low-throughput sequencing using the Sanger method was used to sequence random transcripts, producing expressed sequence tags (ESTs).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The Sanger method of sequencing was predominant until the advent of high-throughput methods such as sequencing by synthesis (Solexa/Illumina).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] ESTs came to prominence during the 1990s as an efficient method to determine the gene content of an organism without sequencing the entire genome.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Amounts of individual transcripts were quantified using Northern blotting, nylon membrane arrays, and later reverse transcriptase quantitative PCR (RT-qPCR) methods, but these methods are laborious and can only capture a tiny subsection of a transcriptome.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Consequently, the manner in which a transcriptome as a whole is expressed and regulated remained unknown until higher-throughput techniques were developed.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The word "transcriptome" was first used in the 1990s.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] In 1995, one of the earliest sequencing-based transcriptomic methods was developed, serial analysis of gene expression (SAGE), which worked by Sanger sequencing of concatenated random transcript fragments.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcripts were quantified by matching the fragments to known genes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] A variant of SAGE using high-throughput sequencing techniques, called digital gene expression analysis, was also briefly used.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] However, these methods were largely overtaken by high throughput sequencing of entire transcripts, which provided additional information on transcript structure such as splice variants.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The dominant contemporary techniques, microarrays and RNA-Seq, were developed in the mid-1990s and 2000s.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarrays that measure the abundances of a defined set of transcripts via their hybridisation to an array of complementary probes were first published in 1995.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarray technology allowed the assay of thousands of transcripts simultaneously and at a greatly reduced cost per gene and labour saving.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Both spotted oligonucleotide arrays and Affymetrix high-density arrays were the method of choice for transcriptional profiling until the late 2000s.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Over this period, a range of microarrays were produced to cover known genes in model or economically important organisms.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Advances in design and manufacture of arrays improved the specificity of probes and allowed more genes to be tested on a single array.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Advances in fluorescence detection increased the sensitivity and measurement accuracy for low abundance transcripts.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq is accomplished by reverse transcribing RNA *in vitro* and sequencing the resulting cDNAs.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcript abundance is derived from the number of counts from each transcript.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The technique has therefore been heavily influenced by the development of high-throughput sequencing technologies.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Massively parallel signature sequencing (MPSS) was an early example based on generating 16–20 bp sequences via a complex series of hybridisations, and was used in 2004 to validate the expression of ten thousand genes in *Arabidopsis thaliana*.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The earliest RNA-Seq work was published in 2006 with one hundred thousand transcripts sequenced using 454 technology.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] This was sufficient coverage to quantify relative transcript abundance.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq began to increase in popularity after 2008 when new Solexa/Illumina technologies allowed one billion transcript sequences to be recorded.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] This yield now allows for the quantification and comparison of human transcriptomes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Generating data on RNA transcripts can be achieved via either of two main principles: sequencing of individual transcripts (ESTs, or RNA-Seq) or hybridisation of transcripts to an ordered array of nucleotide probes (microarrays).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] All transcriptomic methods require RNA to first be isolated from the experimental organism before transcripts can be recorded.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Isolated RNA may additionally be treated with DNase to digest any traces of DNA.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] It is necessary to enrich messenger RNA as total RNA extracts are typically 98% ribosomal RNA.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Enrichment for transcripts can be performed by poly-A affinity methods or by depletion of ribosomal RNA using sequence-specific probes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Degraded RNA may affect downstream results; for example, mRNA enrichment from degraded samples will result in the depletion of 5' mRNA ends and an uneven signal across the length of a transcript.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Snap-freezing of tissue prior to RNA isolation is typical, and care is taken to reduce exposure to RNase enzymes once isolation is complete.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] An expressed sequence tag (EST) is a short nucleotide sequence generated from a single RNA transcript.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA is first copied as complementary DNA (cDNA) by a reverse transcriptase enzyme before the resultant cDNA is sequenced.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Because ESTs can be collected without prior knowledge of the organism from which they come, they can be made from mixtures of organisms or environmental samples.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Although higher-throughput methods are now used, EST libraries commonly provided sequence information for early microarray designs; for example, a barley microarray was designed from 350,000 previously sequenced ESTs.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] These cDNA tags are then joined head-to-tail into long strands (>500 bp) and sequenced using low-throughput, but long read-length methods such as Sanger sequencing.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The sequences are then divided back into their original 11 bp tags using computer software in a process called deconvolution.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] If a high-quality reference genome is available, these tags may be matched to their corresponding gene in the genome.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] If a reference genome is unavailable, the tags can be directly used as diagnostic markers if found to be differentially expressed in a disease state.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The cap analysis gene expression (CAGE) method is a variant of SAGE that sequences tags from the 5' end of an mRNA transcript only.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Therefore, the transcriptional start site of genes can be identified when the tags are aligned to a reference genome.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Identifying gene start sites is of use for promoter analysis and for the cloning of full-length cDNAs.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] SAGE and CAGE methods produce information on more genes than was possible when sequencing single ESTs, but sample preparation and data analysis are typically more labour-intensive.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarrays usually consist of a grid of short nucleotide oligomers, known as "probes", typically arranged on a glass slide.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcript abundance is determined by hybridisation of fluorescently labelled transcripts to these probes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The fluorescence intensity at each probe location on the array indicates the transcript abundance for that probe sequence.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Groups of probes designed to measure the same transcript (i.e., hybridizing a specific transcript in different positions) are usually referred to as "probesets".
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarrays require some genomic knowledge from the organism of interest, for example, in the form of an annotated genome sequence, or a library of ESTs that can be used to generate the probes for the array.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarrays for transcriptomics typically fall into one of two broad categories: low-density spotted arrays or high-density short probe arrays.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcript abundance is inferred from the intensity of fluorescence derived from fluorophore-tagged transcripts that bind to the array.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Spotted low-density arrays typically feature picolitre drops of a range of purified cDNAs arrayed on the surface of a glass slide.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] These probes are longer than those of high-density arrays and cannot identify alternative splicing events.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Spotted arrays use two different fluorophores to label the test and control samples, and the ratio of fluorescence is used to calculate a relative measure of abundance.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] High-density arrays use a single fluorescent label, and each sample is hybridised and detected individually.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] High-density arrays were popularised by the Affymetrix GeneChip array, where each transcript is quantified by several short 25-mer probes that together assay one gene.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] NimbleGen arrays were a high-density array produced by a maskless-photochemistry method, which permitted flexible manufacture of arrays in small or large numbers.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] These arrays had 100,000s of 45 to 85-mer probes and were hybridised with a one-colour labelled sample for expression analysis.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Some designs incorporated up to 12 independent arrays per slide.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq refers to the combination of a high-throughput sequencing methodology with computational methods to capture and quantify transcripts present in an RNA extract.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The nucleotide sequences generated are typically around 100 bp in length, but can range from 30 bp to over 10,000 bp depending on the sequencing method used.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq leverages deep sampling of the transcriptome with many short fragments from a transcriptome to allow computational reconstruction of the original RNA transcript by aligning reads to a reference genome or to each other (de novo assembly).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Both low-abundance and high-abundance RNAs can be quantified in an RNA-Seq experiment (dynamic range of 5 orders of magnitude)—a key advantage over microarray transcriptomes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] In addition, input RNA amounts are much lower for RNA-Seq (nanogram quantity) compared to microarrays (microgram quantity), which allow examination of the transcriptome even at a single-cell resolution when combined with amplification of cDNA.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Theoretically, there is no upper limit of quantification in RNA-Seq, and background noise is very low for 100 bp reads in non-repetitive regions.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq may be used to identify genes within a genome, or identify which genes are active at a particular point in time, and read counts can be used to accurately model the relative gene expression level.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq methodology has constantly improved, primarily through the development of DNA sequencing technologies to increase throughput, accuracy, and read length.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Since the first descriptions in 2006 and 2008, RNA-Seq has been rapidly adopted and overtook microarrays as the dominant transcriptomics technique in 2015.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The quest for transcriptome data at the level of individual cells has driven advances in RNA-Seq library preparation methods, resulting in dramatic advances in sensitivity.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Single-cell transcriptomes are now well described and have even been extended to *in situ* RNA-Seq where transcriptomes of individual cells are directly interrogated in fixed tissues.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq was established in concert with the rapid development of a range of high-throughput DNA sequencing technologies.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] However, before the extracted RNA transcripts are sequenced, several key processing steps are performed.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Methods differ in the use of transcript enrichment, fragmentation, amplification, single or paired-end sequencing, and whether to preserve strand information.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The sensitivity of an RNA-Seq experiment can be increased by enriching classes of RNA that are of interest and depleting known abundant RNAs.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The mRNA molecules can be separated using oligonucleotides probes which bind their poly-A tails.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Alternatively, ribo-depletion can be used to specifically remove abundant but uninformative ribosomal RNAs (rRNAs) by hybridisation to probes tailored to the taxon's specific rRNA sequences (e.g. mammal rRNA, plant rRNA).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] However, ribo-depletion can also introduce some bias via non-specific depletion of off-target transcripts.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Small RNAs, such as micro RNAs, can be purified based on their size by gel electrophoresis and extraction.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Since mRNAs are longer than the read-lengths of typical high-throughput sequencing methods, transcripts are usually fragmented prior to sequencing.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The fragmentation method is a key aspect of sequencing library construction.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Fragmentation may be achieved by chemical hydrolysis, nebulisation, sonication, or reverse transcription with chain-terminating nucleotides.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Alternatively, fragmentation and cDNA tagging may be done simultaneously by using transposase enzymes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] During preparation for sequencing, cDNA copies of transcripts may be amplified by PCR to enrich for fragments that contain the expected 5' and 3' adapter sequences.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Amplification is also used to allow sequencing of very low input amounts of RNA, down to as little as 50 pg in extreme applications.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Spike-in controls of known RNAs can be used for quality control assessment to check library preparation and sequencing, in terms of GC-content, fragment length, as well as the bias due to fragment position within a transcript.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Unique molecular identifiers (UMIs) are short random sequences that are used to individually tag sequence fragments during library preparation so that every tagged fragment is unique.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] UMIs provide an absolute scale for quantification, the opportunity to correct for subsequent amplification bias introduced during library construction, and accurately estimate the initial sample size.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] UMIs are particularly well-suited to single-cell RNA-Seq transcriptomics, where the amount of input RNA is restricted and extended amplification of the sample is required.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Once the transcript molecules have been prepared they can be sequenced in just one direction (single-end) or both directions (paired-end).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] A single-end sequence is usually quicker to produce, cheaper than paired-end sequencing and sufficient for quantification of gene expression levels.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Paired-end sequencing produces more robust alignments/assemblies, which is beneficial for gene annotation and transcript isoform discovery.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Strand-specific RNA-Seq methods preserve the strand information of a sequenced transcript.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Without strand information, reads can be aligned to a gene locus but do not inform in which direction the gene is transcribed.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Stranded-RNA-Seq is useful for deciphering transcription for genes that overlap in different directions and to make more robust gene predictions in non-model organisms.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Legend: NCBI SRA – National center for biotechnology information sequence read archive.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Currently RNA-Seq relies on copying RNA molecules into cDNA molecules prior to sequencing; therefore, the subsequent platforms are the same for transcriptomic and genomic data.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Consequently, the development of DNA sequencing technologies has been a defining feature of RNA-Seq.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Direct sequencing of RNA using nanopore sequencing represents a current state-of-the-art RNA-Seq technique.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Nanopore sequencing of RNA can detect modified bases that would be otherwise masked when sequencing cDNA and also eliminates amplification steps that can otherwise introduce bias.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The sensitivity and accuracy of an RNA-Seq experiment are dependent on the number of reads obtained from each sample.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] A large number of reads are needed to ensure sufficient coverage of the transcriptome, enabling detection of low abundance transcripts.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Experimental design is further complicated by sequencing technologies with a limited output range, the variable efficiency of sequence creation, and variable sequence quality.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Added to those considerations is that every species has a different number of genes and therefore requires a tailored sequence yield for an effective transcriptome.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Early studies determined suitable thresholds empirically, but as the technology matured suitable coverage was predicted computationally by transcriptome saturation.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Somewhat counter-intuitively, the most effective way to improve detection of differential expression in low expression genes is to add more biological replicates rather than adding more reads.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The current benchmarks recommended by the Encyclopedia of DNA Elements (ENCODE) Project are for 70-fold exome coverage for standard RNA-Seq and up to 500-fold exome coverage to detect rare transcripts and isoforms.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomics methods are highly parallel and require significant computation to produce meaningful data for both microarray and RNA-Seq experiments.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarray data is recorded as high-resolution images, requiring feature detection and spectral analysis.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarray raw image files are each about 750 MB in size, while the processed intensities are around 60 MB in size.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Multiple short probes matching a single transcript can reveal details about the intron-exon structure, requiring statistical models to determine the authenticity of the resulting signal.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq studies produce billions of short DNA sequences, which must be aligned to reference genomes composed of millions to billions of base pairs.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] *De novo* assembly of reads within a dataset requires the construction of highly complex sequence graphs.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq operations are highly repetitious and benefit from parallelised computation but modern algorithms mean consumer computing hardware is sufficient for simple transcriptomics experiments that do not require *de novo* assembly of reads.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] A human transcriptome could be accurately captured using RNA-Seq with 30 million 100 bp sequences per sample.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] This example would require approximately 1.8 gigabytes of disk space per sample when stored in a compressed fastq format.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Processed count data for each gene would be much smaller, equivalent to processed microarray intensities.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Sequence data may be stored in public repositories, such as the Sequence Read Archive (SRA).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq datasets can be uploaded via the Gene Expression Omnibus.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Microarray image processing must correctly identify the regular grid of features within an image and independently quantify the fluorescence intensity for each feature.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Image artefacts must be additionally identified and removed from the overall analysis.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Fluorescence intensities directly indicate the abundance of each sequence, since the sequence of each probe on the array is already known.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The first steps of RNA-seq also include similar image processing; however, conversion of images to sequence data is typically handled automatically by the instrument software.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The Illumina sequencing-by-synthesis method results in an array of clusters distributed over the surface of a flow cell.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The flow cell is imaged up to four times during each sequencing cycle, with tens to hundreds of cycles in total.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Flow cell clusters are analogous to microarray spots and must be correctly identified during the early stages of the sequencing process.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] In Roche's pyrosequencing method, the intensity of emitted light determines the number of consecutive nucleotides in a homopolymer repeat.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] There are many variants on these methods, each with a different error profile for the resulting data.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq experiments generate a large volume of raw sequence reads which have to be processed to yield useful information.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Data analysis usually requires a combination of bioinformatics software tools (see also List of RNA-Seq bioinformatics tools) that vary according to the experimental design and goals.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The process can be broken down into four stages: quality control, alignment, quantification, and differential expression.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Most popular RNA-Seq programs are run from a command-line interface, either in a Unix environment or within the R/Bioconductor statistical environment.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Sequence reads are not perfect, so the accuracy of each base in the sequence needs to be estimated for downstream analyses.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Raw data is examined to ensure: quality scores for base calls are high, the GC content matches the expected distribution, short sequence motifs (k-mers) are not over-represented, and the read duplication rate is acceptably low.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Several software options exist for sequence quality analysis, including FastQC and FaQCs.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Abnormalities may be removed (trimming) or tagged for special treatment during later processes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] In order to link sequence read abundance to the expression of a particular gene, transcript sequences are aligned to a reference genome or *de novo* aligned to one another if no reference is available.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The key challenges for alignment software include sufficient speed to permit billions of short sequences to be aligned in a meaningful timeframe, flexibility to recognise and deal with intron splicing of eukaryotic mRNA, and correct assignment of reads that map to multiple locations.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Software advances have greatly addressed these issues, and increases in sequencing read length reduce the chance of ambiguous read alignments.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] A list of currently available high-throughput sequence aligners is maintained by the EBI.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Alignment of primary transcript mRNA sequences derived from eukaryotes to a reference genome requires specialised handling of intron sequences, which are absent from mature mRNA.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Short read aligners perform an additional round of alignments specifically designed to identify splice junctions, informed by canonical splice site sequences and known intron splice site information.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Identification of intron splice junctions prevents reads from being misaligned across splice junctions or erroneously discarded, allowing more reads to be aligned to the reference genome and improving the accuracy of gene expression estimates.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Since gene regulation may occur at the mRNA isoform level, splice-aware alignments also permit detection of isoform abundance changes that would otherwise be lost in a bulked analysis.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Legend: RAM – random access memory; MPI – message passing interface; EST – expressed sequence tag.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Quantification of sequence alignments may be performed at the gene, exon, or transcript level.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Typical outputs include a table of read counts for each feature supplied to the software; for example, for genes in a general feature format file.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Gene and exon read counts may be calculated quite easily using HTSeq, for example.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Quantitation at the transcript level is more complicated and requires probabilistic methods to estimate transcript isoform abundance from short read information; for example, using cufflinks software.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Reads that align equally well to multiple locations must be identified and either removed, aligned to one of the possible locations, or aligned to the most probable location.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Some quantification methods can circumvent the need for an exact alignment of a read to a reference sequence altogether.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The kallisto software method combines pseudoalignment and quantification into a single step that runs 2 orders of magnitude faster than contemporary methods such as those used by tophat/cufflinks software, with less computational burden.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Once quantitative counts of each transcript are available, differential gene expression is measured by normalising, modelling, and statistically analysing the data.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Most tools will read a table of genes and read counts as their input, but some programs, such as cuffdiff, will accept binary alignment map format read alignments as input.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The final outputs of these analyses are gene lists with associated pair-wise tests for differential expression between treatments and the probability estimates of those differences.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomic analyses may be validated using an independent technique, for example, quantitative PCR (qPCR), which is recognisable and statistically assessable.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Gene expression is measured against defined standards both for the gene of interest and control genes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The measurement by qPCR is similar to that obtained by RNA-Seq wherein a value can be calculated for the concentration of a target region in a given sample. qPCR is, however, restricted to amplicons smaller than 300 bp, usually toward the 3' end of the coding region, avoiding the 3'UTR.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] If validation of transcript isoforms is required, an inspection of RNA-Seq read alignments should indicate where qPCR primers might be placed for maximum discrimination.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The measurement of multiple control genes along with the genes of interest produces a stable reference within a biological context. qPCR validation of RNA-Seq data has generally shown that different RNA-Seq methods are highly correlated.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Functional validation of key genes is an important consideration for post transcriptome planning.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Observed gene expression patterns may be functionally linked to a phenotype by an independent knock-down/rescue study in the organism of interest.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomic strategies have seen broad application across diverse areas of biomedical research, including disease diagnosis and profiling.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq approaches have allowed for the large-scale identification of transcriptional start sites, uncovered alternative promoter usage, and novel splicing alterations.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] These regulatory elements are important in human disease and, therefore, defining such variants is crucial to the interpretation of disease-association studies.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq can also identify disease-associated single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs), allele-specific expression, and gene fusions, which contributes to the understanding of disease causal variants.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Retrotransposons are transposable elements which proliferate within eukaryotic genomes through a process involving reverse transcription.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq can provide information about the transcription of endogenous retrotransposons that may influence the transcription of neighboring genes by various epigenetic mechanisms that lead to disease.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Similarly, the potential for using RNA-Seq to understand immune-related disease is expanding rapidly due to the ability to dissect immune cell populations and to sequence T cell and B cell receptor repertoires from patients.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq of human pathogens has become an established method for quantifying gene expression changes, identifying novel virulence factors, predicting antibiotic resistance, and unveiling host-pathogen immune interactions.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] A primary aim of this technology is to develop optimised infection control measures and targeted individualised treatment.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomic analysis has predominantly focused on either the host or the pathogen.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Dual RNA-Seq has been applied to simultaneously profile RNA expression in both the pathogen and host throughout the infection process.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] This technique enables the study of the dynamic response and interspecies gene regulatory networks in both interaction partners from initial contact through to invasion and the final persistence of the pathogen or clearance by the host immune system.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomics allows identification of genes and pathways that respond to and counteract biotic and abiotic environmental stresses.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The non-targeted nature of transcriptomics allows the identification of novel transcriptional networks in complex systems.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] For example, comparative analysis of a range of chickpea lines at different developmental stages identified distinct transcriptional profiles associated with drought and salinity stresses, including identifying the role of transcript isoforms of AP2-EREBP.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Investigation of gene expression during biofilm formation by the fungal pathogen *Candida albicans* revealed a co-regulated set of genes critical for biofilm establishment and maintenance.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomic profiling also provides crucial information on mechanisms of drug resistance.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] The use of transcriptomics is also important to investigate responses in the marine environment.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] In marine ecology, "stress" and "adaptation" have been among the most common research topics, especially related to anthropogenic stress, such as global change and pollution.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Most of the studies in this area have been done in animals, although invertebrates have been underrepresented.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] One issue still is a deficiency in functional genetic studies, which hamper gene annotations, especially for non-model species, and can lead to vague conclusions on the effects of responses studied.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomics is particularly useful for studying how bacterial genes respond to complex plant-associated environments, where adaptation is driven by coordinated regulation of multiple genes rather than single, well-characterized factors.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] In plant–microbe interactions, transcriptomic analyses have identified sets of bacterial genes that are specifically induced during plant colonization or in response to plant-derived signals, many of which lack prior functional annotation and would not be detected using targeted approaches.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] By integrating gene expression data with comparative genomic or community-level analyses, transcriptomics helps link bacterial gene regulation to ecological relevance and adaptive processes in plant-associated niches.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] This approach has proven valuable for identifying previously overlooked bacterial functions involved in stress tolerance, host interaction, and niche adaptation.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] All transcriptomic techniques have been particularly useful in identifying the functions of genes and identifying those responsible for particular phenotypes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomics of *Arabidopsis* ecotypes that hyperaccumulate metals correlated genes involved in metal uptake, tolerance, and homeostasis with the phenotype.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Integration of RNA-Seq datasets across different tissues has been used to improve annotation of gene functions in commercially important organisms (e.g. cucumber) or threatened species (e.g. koala).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Assembly of RNA-Seq reads is not dependent on a reference genome and so is ideal for gene expression studies of non-model organisms with non-existing or poorly developed genomic resources.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] For example, a database of SNPs used in Douglas fir breeding programs was created by *de novo* transcriptome analysis in the absence of a sequenced genome.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Similarly, genes that function in the development of cardiac, muscle, and nervous tissue in lobsters were identified by comparing the transcriptomes of the various tissue types without use of a genome sequence.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] RNA-Seq can also be used to identify previously unknown protein coding regions in existing sequenced genomes.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomics is most commonly applied to the mRNA content of the cell.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] However, the same techniques are equally applicable to non-coding RNAs (ncRNAs) that are not translated into a protein, but instead have direct functions (e.g. roles in protein translation, DNA replication, RNA splicing, and transcriptional regulation).
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Many of these ncRNAs affect disease states, including cancer, cardiovascular, and neurological diseases.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] Transcriptomics studies generate large amounts of data that have potential applications far beyond the original aims of an experiment.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] As such, raw or processed data may be deposited in public databases to ensure their utility for the broader scientific community.
[src:transcriptomics/transcriptomics-technologies] For example, as of 2018, the Gene Expression Omnibus contained millions of experiments.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] In molecular genetics, an **untranslated region** (or **UTR**) refers to either of two sections, one on each side of a coding sequence on a strand of mRNA.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] If it is found on the 5' side, it is called the 5' UTR (or **leader sequence**), or if it is found on the 3' side, it is called the 3' UTR (or **trailer sequence**). mRNA is RNA that carries information from DNA to the ribosome, the site of protein synthesis (translation) within a cell.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The mRNA is initially transcribed from the corresponding DNA sequence and then translated into protein.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] However, several regions of the mRNA are usually not translated into protein, including the 5' and 3' UTRs.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] Although they are called untranslated regions, and do not form the protein-coding region of the gene, uORFs located within the 5' UTR can be translated into peptides.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The 5' UTR is upstream from the coding sequence.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] Within the 5' UTR is a sequence that is recognized by the ribosome which allows the ribosome to bind and initiate translation.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The mechanism of translation initiation differs in prokaryotes and eukaryotes.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The 3' UTR is found immediately following the translation stop codon.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The 3' UTR plays a critical role in translation termination as well as post-transcriptional modification.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] These often long sequences were once thought to be useless or junk mRNA that has simply accumulated over evolutionary time.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] However, it is now known that the untranslated region of mRNA is involved in many regulatory aspects of gene expression in eukaryotic organisms.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The importance of these non-coding regions is supported by evolutionary reasoning, as natural selection would have otherwise eliminated this unusable RNA.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] It is important to distinguish the 5' and 3' UTRs from other non-protein-coding RNA.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] Within the coding sequence of pre-mRNA, there can be found sections of RNA that will not be included in the protein product.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] These sections of RNA are called introns.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The RNA that results from RNA splicing is a sequence of exons.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The reason why introns are not considered untranslated regions is that the introns are spliced out in the process of RNA splicing.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The introns are not included in the mature mRNA molecule that will undergo translation and are thus considered non-protein-coding RNA.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The untranslated regions of mRNA became a subject of study as early as the late 1970s, after the first mRNA molecule was fully sequenced.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] In 1978, the 5' UTR of the human gamma-globin mRNA was fully sequenced.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] In 1980, a study was conducted on the 3' UTR of the duplicated human alpha-globin genes.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The untranslated region is seen in prokaryotes and eukaryotes, although the length and composition may vary.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] In prokaryotes, the 5' UTR is typically between 3 and 10 nucleotides long.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] In eukaryotes, the 5' UTR can be hundreds to thousands of nucleotides long.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] This is consistent with the higher complexity of the genomes of eukaryotes compared to prokaryotes.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The poly-A tail is essential for keeping the mRNA from being degraded.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] Although there is variation in lengths of both the 5' and 3' UTR, it has been seen that the 5' UTR length is more highly conserved in evolution than the 3' UTR length.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The 5' UTR of prokaryotes consists of the Shine–Dalgarno sequence (5'-AGGAGGU-3').
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] This sequence is found 3-10 base pairs upstream from the initiation codon, the start site of the translation into protein.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The 5' UTR of eukaryotes is more complex than that of prokaryotes.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] It contains a Kozak consensus sequence (ACCAUGG) including the initiation codon (AUG), the start site of the translation into protein.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] The importance of these untranslated regions of mRNA is just beginning to be understood.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] Various medical studies are being conducted that have found connections between mutations in untranslated regions and increased risk for developing a particular disease, such as cancer.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] For example, associations between polymorphisms in the HLA-G 3′UTR region and development of colorectal cancer have been discovered.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] Single Nucleotide Polymorphisms in the 3' UTR of another gene have also been associated with susceptibility to preterm birth.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] Mutations in the 3' UTR of the APP gene are related to development of cerebral amyloid angiopathy.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] Through the recent study of untranslated regions, general information has been gathered about the nature and function of these elements.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] However, there is still much that is unknown about these regions of mRNA.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] Since the regulation of gene expression is critical in the proper function of cells, this is an area of study that needs to be investigated further.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] It is important to consider that mutations in 3' untranslated regions have the potential to alter the expression of several genes that may appear unrelated.
[src:transcriptomics/untranslated-region] We are only beginning to understand the links between proper untranslated region function, and disease states of cells.
